Ontogenetic Migration and Habitat Selection by Invasive Lionfish

Alisha Naidu1, Juan Carlos Villaseñor-Derbez2
1Lynbrook High School, 1280 Johnson Avenue, San Jose, CA 95129
alisha415naidu@gmail.com
2Bren School of Environmental Science and Management, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA 93106


Abstract

The introduction of invasive lionfish into the Western Atlantic greatly reduced local fish populations through predation, representing a major threat to native organisms and ecosystem managers alike. Although observational evidence suggests that lionfish size increases with depths, this pattern has not been formally addressed. Understanding habitat utilization patterns of larger, older and more fecund lionfish might shed light on ways to maximize the efficiency of lionfish culling programs. In this study, we analyzed data from ten locations in the Mexican Caribbean to determine the pattern between lionfish size, age, and the depth at which they live. We explored two possible explanations for the observed patterns: ontogenetic migration and harvesting effects. All locations signified a general presence of larger lionfish in deeper areas, confirming previous observations. Not enough evidence was found to suggest that the pattern is caused by culling. However, a likely explanation is ontogenetic migration, indicated by the presence of older lionfish in deeper waters. Results from this study highlight the importance of focusing management strategies on deeper waters to maximize effectiveness of lionfish removal programs.

Introduction

Invasive species are widely recognized as a major threat to the health and biodiversity of marine ecosystems. Yet, less than 16% of marine ecosystems are free of non-native species (Molnar et al. 2008). Non-native species tend to upset the balance of the ecosystem they invade by displacing the native populations and disrupting ecological processes, with associated costs of up to 120 billion USD annually (Pimentel et al. 2005). Lionfish, an invasive species originating in the Indo-Pacific and spreading throughout the western Atlantic, are no exception. Lionfish impact invaded areas by reducing native populations to levels of endangerment through predation and competition, affecting the health of coral reefs and of the overall ecosystem (Green et al. 2012).

The success of lionfish management programs lies in understanding habitat utilization patterns. Current invasion management programs are limited by the depth at which divers are able to go to, thus, removal efforts focus solely on the shallow areas that lionfish populate. Previously, lionfish were believed to live only in shallow waters, but recently, observations of lionfish spotted in deeper areas have surfaced (Gress et al. 2017; Andradi-Brown et al. 2017). More importantly, anecdotal evidence suggests that larger and more fecund organisms live in deeper waters. However, no formal quantification of this pattern has been reported. This poses a major problem in the effectiveness of the programs, as larger lionfish remain safe from culling programs. As a result, lionfish spread rapidly, facilitated by their lack of predators, opportunistic feeding habits, and fecundity. With most lionfish management programs focusing mainly on controlling lionfish populations in shallower waters (< 30 m), the refuge provided for lionfish by deeper waters is often overlooked in techniques regarding lionfish containment. Without more attention being focused on deeper waters, lionfish will continue to cause destruction within marine ecosystems. However, with research being done on habitat utilization of lionfish, management programs may be able to minimize the impact lionfish have on marine ecosystems by focusing their efforts on deeper waters.

This study evaluates the relationship between lionfish size and the depth at which they live, and poses the hypotheses of ontogenetic migration and shallow-biased culling as possible explanations for the size-depth relationship. Analyzing this relationship before and after culling does not provide a comprehensive analysis, as the lengths of the lionfish are not exact, however, it is suggested by the data that ontogenetic migration may be one of the larger factors which are causing the pattern. Our focal analysis on the Mexican Caribbean may help us better understand how we can target lionfish and eliminate them from non-native areas.

Methods

Data Collection
Our study took place at ten different sites throughout the Mexican Caribbean. We caught 109 lionfish using handheld nets and numbered containers, with no regard to age, size, depth, gender, or other factors. The depth (nearest 0.1 m) and exact location (latitude and longitude) at which they were found were immediately recorded upon capture, and their length (to the nearest 1 mm) and weight (nearest 0.01 g) were measured upon reaching the surface.
To convert the length of the lionfish to the age, we used the length-based von Bertalanffy growth equation and the von Bertalanffy growth parameters (L∞ = 420, K = 0.88, t0 = 0.11) specified for Yucatan (Johnson and Swenarton 2016). \[A = t_0 + \frac{log(1-\frac LL_∞)}{-K}\] With data for lionfish length, weight, depth, and age, we began the data analysis portion of our research.

Data Analysis

Using RStudio, we looked for a pattern between the data by plotting three different graphs: length versus depth, weight versus depth, and age versus depth. After creating these graphs, we used linear regressions and Pearson’s correlation to fit a linear model to the graphs of the relationships between size, age, and depth. The stargazer package in R (Hlavac, 2018) was used to create a table displaying the significance of the linear patterns (See Figure #). All data analyses were performed in R Version 3.5.0, using ggplot2 for data visualization (R Core Team, 2018).

While trying to analyze the relationship between size and depth before and after culling of lionfish in the Mexican Caribbean, it was determined that the data collected is insufficient to confirm a pattern of deepening caused by shallow-biased culling. Thus, more research should be done on the effect of culling on the habitat selection of lionfish, with attention being focused on including data from lower depths and larger lionfish to be accurate.

Results

Linf = 420
T0 = 0.11
K = -0.88
library(tidyverse)
fish <- read_csv("RMP_lionfish.csv", col_types = cols()) %>% 
  select(id, site, location, latitude, longitude, depth, temperature, total_length, total_weight) %>%
  mutate(age = T0 + (log(1-(total_length/Linf))/K), 
         logTL = log(total_length),
         logDepth = log(depth),
         logAge = log(age),
         logTW = log(total_weight)) %>%
  distinct()

Lionfish Length and Depth

ggplot(data= fish, mapping = aes(x = total_length, y = depth)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(fill = location), size = 4, alpha = 0.8, shape = 21) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x="Length (mm)", y="Depth (m)", fill="Location") +
  ggtitle("Lionfish Length-Depth Relationship") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Lionfish Age and Depth

ggplot(data=fish, mapping = aes(x=age, y=depth)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(fill = location), size = 4, alpha = 0.7, shape = 21) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x="Age (years)", y = "Depth (m)", fill = "Location") +
  ggtitle("Lionfish Age-Depth Relationship") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Discussion and Conclusion

depth_vec <- seq(0, 40, by = 5)

# Load data, mutate fecundity (f) and make depth into bins (depth_bin)
# then group by depth and calculate total egg production

fecundity_data <- read.csv("RMP_lionfish.csv") %>%
    mutate(f = -58265 + (308.67 * total_length),
                  depth_bin = findInterval(depth, depth_vec)) %>%
    group_by(depth_bin) %>%
    summarize(total_f = sum(f))

# Plot fecundity at depth
ggplot(data = fecundity_data, mapping = aes(x = depth_bin, y = total_f), size = 4, alpha = 0.8, shape = 21) +
    geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x="Depth", y="Fecundity") +
  ggtitle("Lionfish Depth-Fecundity Relationship") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
